WEBVTT

00:01.220 --> 00:05.200
Chapter 6 of the Meditations of Marcus Aurelius.

00:05.720 --> 00:07.180
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:07.580 --> 00:09.780
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:10.220 --> 00:14.920
For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:15.820 --> 00:20.260
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus.

00:20.340 --> 00:21.920
Translated by George Long.

00:22.420 --> 00:23.340
Chapter 6.

00:24.820 --> 00:29.020
The substance of the universe is obedient and compliant, and the reason which governs

00:29.020 --> 00:33.900
it has in itself no cause for doing evil, for it has no malice, nor does it do evil

00:33.900 --> 00:36.760
to anything, nor is anything harmed by it.

00:37.020 --> 00:40.160
But all things are made and perfected according to this reason.

00:42.820 --> 00:47.120
Let it make no difference to thee whether thou art cold or warm, if thou art doing

00:47.120 --> 00:53.780
thy duty, and whether thou art drowsy or satisfied with sleep, and whether ill-spoken or praised,

00:54.520 --> 01:00.160
and whether dying or doing something else, for it is one of the acts of this life, this act by

01:00.160 --> 01:05.960
which we die, it is sufficient then in this act also to do well what we have in hand.

01:08.360 --> 01:13.500
Look within, let neither the peculiar quality of anything nor its value escape thee.

01:15.660 --> 01:19.540
All existing things soon change, and they will either be reduced to vapor,

01:20.000 --> 01:23.340
if indeed all substance is one, or they will be dispersed.

01:25.160 --> 01:30.920
The reason which governs knows what its own disposition is, and what it does, and on what

01:30.920 --> 01:32.080
material it works.

01:34.840 --> 01:39.320
The best way of avenging thyself is not to become like the wrongdoer.

01:41.320 --> 01:45.460
Take pleasure in one thing and rest in it, in passing from one social act to another

01:45.460 --> 01:47.500
social act, thinking of God.

01:49.340 --> 01:54.600
The ruling principle is that which rouses and turns itself, and while it makes itself

01:54.600 --> 01:59.540
such as it is, and such as it wills to be, it also makes everything which happens to

01:59.540 --> 02:02.420
appear itself to be such as it wills.

02:04.500 --> 02:08.500
In conformity to the nature of the universe, every single thing is accomplished.

02:09.480 --> 02:13.740
For certainly it is not in conformity to any other nature that each thing is accomplished,

02:13.740 --> 02:20.040
either a nature which externally comprehends this, or a nature which is comprehended within

02:20.040 --> 02:24.120
this nature, or a nature external and independent of this.

02:27.520 --> 02:33.760
The universe is either a confusion and a mutual involution of things, and a dispersion, or

02:33.760 --> 02:36.200
it is unity and order and providence.

02:36.640 --> 02:41.740
If, then, it is the former, why do I desire to tarry in a fortuitous combination of things

02:41.740 --> 02:47.040
in such a disorder, and why do I care about anything else than how I shall at last become

02:47.040 --> 02:52.480
earth, and why am I disturbed for the dispersion of my elements will happen whatever I do?

02:53.120 --> 03:00.160
But if the other supposition is true, I venerate, and I am firm, and I trust in him who governs.

03:01.400 --> 03:06.500
When thou hast been compelled by circumstances to be disturbed in a manner, quickly return

03:06.500 --> 03:11.560
to thyself, and do not continue out of tune longer than the compulsion lasts, for that

03:11.560 --> 03:15.900
thou wilt have more mastery over the harmony by continually recurring to it.

03:18.680 --> 03:23.060
If thou hadst a stepmother and a mother at the same time, thou wouldest be dutiful to

03:23.060 --> 03:26.840
thy stepmother, but thou wouldest constantly return to thy mother.

03:27.440 --> 03:31.340
Let the court and philosophy now be to thee stepmother and mother.

03:31.900 --> 03:37.520
Return to philosophy frequently, and repose in her, through whom what thou meetest with

03:37.520 --> 03:41.760
in the court appears to thee tolerable, and thou appearest tolerable in the court.

03:45.140 --> 03:51.140
When we have meat before us, and such eatables, we receive the impression that this is the

03:51.140 --> 03:56.740
dead body of a fish, and this is the dead body of a bird, or of a pig, and again that

03:56.740 --> 04:02.260
this Phalernian is only a little grape juice, and this purple robe some sheep's wool dyed

04:02.260 --> 04:03.680
with the blood of a shellfish.

04:04.420 --> 04:08.540
Such then are these impressions, and they reach the things themselves and penetrate

04:08.540 --> 04:11.620
them, and so we see what kind of things they are.

04:12.400 --> 04:17.100
Just in the same way, ought we to act all through life, and where there are things which

04:17.100 --> 04:21.280
appear most worthy of our approbation, we ought to lay them bare, and look at their

04:21.280 --> 04:25.020
worthlessness, and strip them of all the words by which they are exalted.

04:25.900 --> 04:31.580
For outward show is a wonderful perverter of the reason, and when thou art most sure

04:31.580 --> 04:36.300
that thou art employed about things worth thy pains, it is then that it cheats thee

04:36.300 --> 04:36.720
most.

04:37.720 --> 04:41.320
Consider, then, what Crates says of Xenocrates himself.

04:44.160 --> 04:48.480
Most of the things which the multitude admire are referred to objects of the most general

04:48.480 --> 04:54.980
kind, those which are held together by cohesion or natural organization, such as stones, wood,

04:55.320 --> 05:00.440
fig trees, vines, olives, but those which are admired by men, who are a little more

05:00.440 --> 05:05.260
reasonable, are referred to the things which are held together by a living principle, as

05:05.260 --> 05:07.140
flocks, herds.

05:07.420 --> 05:12.500
Those which are admired by men, who are still more instructed, are the things which are

05:12.500 --> 05:19.280
held together by a rational soul, not, however, a universal soul, for rational, so far as

05:19.280 --> 05:25.000
it is a soul skilled in some art, or expert in some other way, or simply rational so far

05:25.000 --> 05:27.040
as it possesses a number of slaves.

05:27.040 --> 05:33.840
But he who values a rational soul, a soul universal and fitted for political life, regards

05:33.840 --> 05:40.160
nothing else except this, and above all things he keeps his soul in a condition and in an

05:40.160 --> 05:46.120
actively conformable to reason and social life, and he cooperates to this end with those

05:46.120 --> 05:48.180
who are of the same kind as himself.

05:50.000 --> 05:55.380
Some things are hurrying into existence, others are hurrying out of it, and of that which

05:55.380 --> 05:59.160
is coming into existence, part is already extinguished.

05:59.320 --> 06:04.300
Motions and changes are continually renewing the world, such as the uninterrupted course

06:04.300 --> 06:07.160
of time is always renewing the infinite duration of ages.

06:08.000 --> 06:13.680
In this flowing stream then, on which there is no abiding, what is there of the things

06:13.680 --> 06:16.800
which hurry by on which a man would set a high price?

06:17.240 --> 06:21.600
It would be just as if a man should fall in love with one of the sparrows which fly by,

06:22.000 --> 06:24.020
but it is already passed out of sight.

06:24.900 --> 06:30.480
Something of this kind is the very life of every man, like the exhalation of the blood

06:30.480 --> 06:32.100
and the respiration of the air.

06:33.000 --> 06:38.560
Such as it is to once have drawn in the air and to have given it back, which we do every

06:38.560 --> 06:44.420
moment, just the same is it with the whole respiratory power which thou didst receive

06:44.420 --> 06:49.680
at thy birth yesterday and the day before, to give it back to the elemental from which

06:49.680 --> 06:51.180
thou didst first draw it.

06:53.180 --> 06:58.900
Neither is transpiration, as in plants, a thing to be valued, nor respiration, as in

06:58.900 --> 07:03.920
domesticated animals and wild beasts, nor the receiving of impressions by the appearances

07:03.920 --> 07:09.920
of things, nor being moved by desires, as puppets by strings, nor assembling in herds,

07:10.140 --> 07:15.900
nor being nourished by food, for this is just like the act of separating and parting with

07:15.900 --> 07:17.040
the useless part of the food.

07:17.860 --> 07:19.940
What, then, is worth being valued?

07:20.280 --> 07:22.120
To be received with clapping of hands?

07:22.740 --> 07:27.540
No, neither must we value the clapping of tongues, for the praise which comes from the

07:27.540 --> 07:29.160
many is the clapping of tongues.

07:30.920 --> 07:35.140
Suppose, then, that thou hast given up this worthless thing called fame.

07:35.300 --> 07:37.520
What remains that is worth valuing?

07:38.420 --> 07:43.400
This, in my opinion, to move thyself and to restrain thyself in conformity to thy proper

07:43.400 --> 07:49.540
constitution, to which end both all employments and arts lead, for every art aims at this,

07:49.820 --> 07:54.280
that the thing which has been made should be adapted to the work for which it has been

07:54.280 --> 07:59.460
made, and both the vine-planner who looks after the vine and the horse-breaker and he

07:59.460 --> 08:01.480
who trains the dog seeks this end.

08:02.380 --> 08:08.120
But the education and the teaching of youth aim at something, and this, then, is the value

08:08.120 --> 08:09.500
of the education and the teaching.

08:10.780 --> 08:14.100
And if this is well, thou wilt not seek anything else.

08:14.720 --> 08:17.280
Wilt thou not cease to value many other things, too?

08:17.600 --> 08:22.500
Then thou wilt neither be free nor sufficient for thy own happiness, nor without passion.

08:23.600 --> 08:27.960
For of necessity thou must be envious, jealous, and suspicious of those who can take away

08:27.960 --> 08:32.920
those things and plot against those who have that which is valued by thee.

08:32.920 --> 08:39.860
Of necessity a man must be altogether in a state of perturbation who wants any of these

08:39.860 --> 08:43.500
things, and besides he must often find fault with the gods.

08:44.580 --> 08:49.460
But to reverence and honor thy own mind will make thee content with thyself, and in harmony

08:49.460 --> 08:54.860
with society, in agreement with the gods, that is, praising all that they give and have

08:54.860 --> 08:55.240
ordered.

08:57.760 --> 09:02.200
Above, below, all around are the movements of the elements.

09:02.940 --> 09:05.200
But the motion of virtue is in none of these.

09:05.760 --> 09:10.780
It is something more divine, and advancing by a way hardly observed, it goes happily

09:10.780 --> 09:11.600
on its road.

09:13.900 --> 09:15.220
How strangely men act!

09:15.660 --> 09:19.520
They will not praise those who are living at the same time and living with themselves.

09:20.340 --> 09:25.300
But to be themselves praised by posterity, by those whom they have never seen or will

09:25.300 --> 09:27.840
ever see, this they set much value on.

09:28.520 --> 09:32.720
But this is very much the same as if thou shouldest be grieved because those who have

09:32.720 --> 09:35.180
lived before thee did not praise thee.

09:37.640 --> 09:42.200
If a thing is difficult to be accomplished by thyself, do not think that it is impossible

09:42.200 --> 09:42.840
for man.

09:43.780 --> 09:48.780
But if anything is possible for man, and conformable to his nature, think that this can be attained

09:48.780 --> 09:50.080
by thyself, too.

09:52.400 --> 09:57.200
In the gymnastic exercises, suppose that a man has torn thee with his nails, and by

09:57.200 --> 09:59.260
dashing against thy head has inflicted a wound.

10:00.020 --> 10:05.840
Well, we neither show any signs of vexation, nor are we offended, nor do we suspect him

10:05.840 --> 10:07.380
afterward as a treacherous fellow.

10:08.120 --> 10:13.160
And yet we are on our guard against him, not, however, as an enemy, nor with suspicion,

10:13.740 --> 10:15.460
but we quietly get out of his way.

10:16.400 --> 10:20.160
Something like this let their behavior be in all other parts of life.

10:20.520 --> 10:26.100
Let us overlook many things in those who are like antagonists in the gymnasium, for it

10:26.100 --> 10:30.900
is in our power, as I said, to get out of the way and to have no suspicion or hatred.

10:33.840 --> 10:39.240
If a man is able to convince me and show me that he do not think or act right, I will

10:39.240 --> 10:43.920
gladly change, for I seek the truth by which no man was ever injured.

10:43.920 --> 10:47.880
But he is injured who abides in his error and ignorance.

10:50.200 --> 10:54.780
I do my duty, other things trouble me not, for they are either things without life or

10:54.780 --> 10:58.580
things without reason, or things that have rambled and know not the way.

11:00.140 --> 11:05.020
As to the animals which have no reason, and generally all things and objects, do thou,

11:05.280 --> 11:09.740
since thou hast reason and they have none, make use of them with a generous and liberal

11:09.740 --> 11:15.920
spirit, but towards human beings, as they have reason, behave in a social spirit, and

11:15.920 --> 11:20.960
on all occasions call on the gods, and do not perplex thyself about the length of time

11:20.960 --> 11:25.360
in which thou shalt do this, for even three hours so spent are sufficient.

11:28.140 --> 11:33.440
Alexander the Macedonian and his groom by death were brought to the same state, for

11:33.440 --> 11:38.080
either they were received among the same seminal principles of the universe, or they were alike

11:38.080 --> 11:39.800
dispersed among the atoms.

11:42.120 --> 11:46.520
Consider how many things in the same indivisible time take place in each of us, things which

11:46.520 --> 11:51.680
concern the body and things which concern the soul, and so that we will not wonder if

11:51.680 --> 11:56.720
many more things, or rather all things which come into existence in that which is the one

11:56.720 --> 12:01.120
and all which we call Cosmos, exist in it at the same time.

12:02.740 --> 12:09.040
If any man should propose to thee the question, how the name Antoninus is written, wouldest

12:09.040 --> 12:13.300
thou with the straining of the voice utter each letter? What then if they grow angry,

12:13.640 --> 12:18.600
wilt thou grow angry too? Wilt thou not go on with composure and number every letter?

12:19.860 --> 12:26.540
Just so then is this life also remember that every duty is made up of certain parts. These

12:26.540 --> 12:30.920
things it is thy duty to observe, and without being disturbed or showing anger towards

12:30.920 --> 12:36.160
those who are angry with thee, to go on thy way and finish that which is set before thee.

12:38.380 --> 12:43.040
How cruel it is not to allow men to strive after the things which appear to them to be

12:43.040 --> 12:48.400
suitable to thy nature and profitable. Yet in a manner thou dost not allow them to do

12:48.400 --> 12:53.460
this, when thou art vexed because they do wrong. For they are certainly moved towards

12:53.460 --> 12:57.320
the things which they suppose them to be suitable to their nature and profitable to

12:57.320 --> 13:03.000
them. But it is not so. Teach them then, and show them without being angry.

13:05.460 --> 13:10.880
Death is the cessation of the impression through the senses, and of the pulling of the strings

13:10.880 --> 13:16.100
which move the appetites, and of the discursive movements of the thoughts, and of the service

13:16.100 --> 13:23.220
to the flesh. It is a shame for the soul to be the first to give way in this life, when

13:23.220 --> 13:24.640
thy body does not give way.

13:27.300 --> 13:33.200
Take care that thou art not made into a Caesar, that thou art not died with this die, for

13:33.200 --> 13:39.400
such things happen. Keep thyself then simple, good, pure, serious, free from affectation,

13:40.180 --> 13:45.560
a friend of justice, a worshiper of the gods, kind, affectionate, strenuous in all proper

13:45.560 --> 13:53.060
acts. Strive to continue to be such as philosophy wished to make thee. Reverence the gods and

13:53.060 --> 14:00.460
help men. Short is life. There is only one fruit in this tureen life, a pious disposition

14:00.460 --> 14:07.280
and social acts. Do everything as a disciple of Antoninus. Remember his constancy in every

14:07.280 --> 14:13.640
act which was conformable to reason, and his evenness in all things, and his piety, and

14:13.640 --> 14:19.240
the serenity of his continence, and his sweetness, and his disregard of empty fame, and his efforts

14:19.240 --> 14:24.880
to understand things, and how he would never let anything pass without having first, most

14:24.880 --> 14:29.960
carefully examined it and clearly understood it, and how he bore with those who blamed

14:29.960 --> 14:35.040
him unjustly without blaming them in return, and how he did nothing in a hurry, and how

14:35.040 --> 14:41.040
he listened not to calumnies, and how exact an examiner of manners and actions he was,

14:41.440 --> 14:48.700
and not given to reproach people, nor timid, nor suspicious, nor asophist, and with how

14:48.700 --> 14:54.980
little he was satisfied, such as lodging, bed, dress, food, servants, and how laborious

14:54.980 --> 15:00.820
and patient, and how he was able, on account of his sparing diet, to hold out to the evening

15:00.820 --> 15:07.080
without even requiring to relieve himself by any evacuations except at the usual hour,

15:07.640 --> 15:11.940
and with his firmness and uniformity in his friendships, and how he tolerated freedom

15:11.940 --> 15:17.480
of speech in those who opposed his opinions, and the pleasure that he had when any man

15:17.480 --> 15:22.040
showed him anything better, and how religious he was without superstition.

15:22.680 --> 15:27.500
Imitate all this that thou mayest have as good a conscience when thy last hour comes,

15:27.860 --> 15:28.740
as he had.

15:32.020 --> 15:37.000
Return to thy sober senses, and call thyself back, when thou hast roused thyself from

15:37.000 --> 15:42.860
sleep, and hast perceived that they were only dreams which troubled thee, now in thy waking

15:42.860 --> 15:47.880
hour's look at these, the things about thee, as thou didst look at those, the dreams.

15:49.480 --> 15:51.480
I consist of a little body and soul.

15:51.940 --> 15:56.420
Now to this little body all things are indifferent, for it is not able to perceive differences,

15:57.240 --> 16:01.640
but to the understanding those things only are indifferent, which are not the works of

16:01.640 --> 16:02.460
its own activity.

16:03.340 --> 16:07.840
But whatever things are the works of its own activity, all these things are in its power,

16:08.500 --> 16:12.660
and of these however only those which are done with reference to the present, for as

16:12.660 --> 16:17.480
to the future and the past activities of the mind, even these are for the present indifferent.

16:20.580 --> 16:25.900
Neither the labor, which the hand does, nor that of the foot is contrary to nature, so

16:25.900 --> 16:30.160
long as the foot does the foot's work and the hand the hand's.

16:30.480 --> 16:35.640
So then neither to a man, as a man is his labor contrary to nature, as long as he does

16:35.640 --> 16:40.980
the things of a man, but if the labor is not contrary to his nature, neither is it an evil

16:40.980 --> 16:41.600
to him.

16:43.600 --> 16:47.620
How many pleasures have been enjoyed by robbers, patricides, tyrants?

16:50.580 --> 16:55.440
Dost thou not see how the handicraftsmen accommodate themselves up to a certain point to those

16:55.440 --> 16:56.880
which are not skilled in their craft?

16:57.460 --> 17:01.340
Nevertheless, they cling to the reason, the principles of their art, and do not endure

17:01.340 --> 17:02.420
to depart from it.

17:03.540 --> 17:07.600
Is it not strange if the architect and the physician shall have more respect to the reason,

17:07.600 --> 17:12.140
the principles of their own arts, than man to his own reason, which is common to him

17:12.140 --> 17:12.800
and the gods?

17:15.180 --> 17:18.580
Asia, Europe, are corners of the universe.

17:19.220 --> 17:21.220
All the sea a drop in the universe.

17:21.800 --> 17:24.080
Athos, a little clod in the universe.

17:24.800 --> 17:27.160
All the present time is a point in eternity.

17:28.320 --> 17:30.940
All things are little, changeable, perishable.

17:31.640 --> 17:37.540
All things come from thence, from that universal ruling power, either directly proceeding or

17:37.540 --> 17:38.420
by way of sequence.

17:38.960 --> 17:43.440
And, accordingly, the lion's gaping jaws, and that which is poisonous, and every harmful

17:43.440 --> 17:48.160
thing, as a thorn, as mud, are afterproducts of the grand and beautiful.

17:49.180 --> 17:53.880
Do not imagine, then, that they are of another kind from that which thou dost venerate, but

17:53.880 --> 17:56.200
form a just opinion of the source of all.

17:58.560 --> 18:03.220
He who has seen present things has seen all, both everything which has taken place from

18:03.220 --> 18:09.100
all eternity, and everything which will be for time without end, for all things are of

18:09.100 --> 18:11.440
one kin and of one form.

18:14.540 --> 18:18.400
Frequently consider the connection of all things in the universe in their relation to

18:18.400 --> 18:18.880
one another.

18:19.740 --> 18:23.760
For, in a manner, all things are implicated with one another, and all, in this way, are

18:23.760 --> 18:24.800
friendly to one another.

18:25.220 --> 18:30.760
For one thing comes in order after another, and this is by virtue of the active movement

18:30.760 --> 18:34.240
and mutual composition and the unity of the substance.

18:36.220 --> 18:40.860
Adapt thyself to the things with which thy lot has been cast, and the men among whom

18:40.860 --> 18:42.680
thou hast received thy portion.

18:43.260 --> 18:45.120
Love them, but do it truly.

18:47.460 --> 18:53.400
Every instrument, too, vessel, if it does that for which it has been made, is well,

18:53.760 --> 18:56.240
and yet he who made it is not there.

18:56.240 --> 19:01.220
But in all things which are held together by nature, there is within, and there abides

19:01.220 --> 19:03.660
in them, the power which made them.

19:04.860 --> 19:09.460
Wherefore, the more it is fit to reverence this power, and to think that, if thou dost

19:09.460 --> 19:14.220
live and act according to its will, everything in thee is in conformity to intelligence.

19:15.160 --> 19:19.940
And thus also in the universe the things which belong to it are in conformity to intelligence.

19:21.960 --> 19:26.420
Whatever of the things which are not within thy power thou shalt suppose to be good for

19:26.420 --> 19:27.460
thee, or evil.

19:28.100 --> 19:33.620
It must of necessity be that, if such a bad thing befall thee, or the loss of such a good

19:33.620 --> 19:39.360
thing, thou wilt blame the gods, and hate men, too, those who are the cause of the misfortune,

19:39.460 --> 19:43.220
or the loss, or those who are suspected of being likely to be the cause.

19:43.820 --> 19:49.920
And indeed we do much injustice, because we make a difference between those things, because

19:49.920 --> 19:51.760
we do not regard these things as indifferent.

19:53.420 --> 19:58.560
But if we judge only those things which are in our power to be good or bad, there remains

19:58.560 --> 20:03.420
no reason either for finding fault with God, or standing in a hostile attitude to man.

20:05.820 --> 20:11.100
We are all working together to one end, some with knowledge and design, and others without

20:11.100 --> 20:17.100
knowing what they do, as men also when they are asleep, of whom it is Heraclius, I think,

20:17.100 --> 20:21.760
who says that there are laborers and cooperators in the things which take place in the universe.

20:22.800 --> 20:27.980
But men cooperate after different fashions, and even those cooperate abundantly, who find

20:27.980 --> 20:32.000
fault with what happens, and those who try to oppose it and to hinder it.

20:32.460 --> 20:35.140
For the universe has need even of such men as these.

20:35.880 --> 20:40.780
It remains then for thee to understand among what kind of workman thou placest thyself.

20:41.220 --> 20:46.760
For he who rules all things will certainly make a right use of thee, and he will receive

20:46.760 --> 20:52.420
thee among some part of the cooperators, and of those whose labors conduce to one end.

20:53.060 --> 20:57.820
But be not thou such a part as the mean and ridiculous verse in the play which Prisippus

20:57.820 --> 20:58.660
speaks of.

21:00.800 --> 21:03.660
Does the sun undertake to do the work of the rain?

21:04.400 --> 21:07.480
Or ice Galapias, the work of the fruit-bearer?

21:07.800 --> 21:12.520
And how is it with respect to each of the stars, are they not different, and yet they

21:12.520 --> 21:14.280
work together to the same end?

21:17.100 --> 21:22.060
If the gods have determined about me, and about the things which must happen to me,

21:22.300 --> 21:23.480
they have determined well.

21:24.020 --> 21:27.540
For it is not easy even to imagine a deity without forethought.

21:28.260 --> 21:32.100
And as to doing me harm, why should they have any desire towards that?

21:32.480 --> 21:36.680
For what advantage would result to them from this, or to the whole, which is the special

21:36.680 --> 21:37.880
object of their providence?

21:38.520 --> 21:42.620
But if they have not determined about me individually, they have certainly determined

21:42.620 --> 21:47.780
about the whole at least, and the things which happen by way of sequence in this general

21:47.780 --> 21:51.280
arrangement I ought to accept with pleasure, and to be content with them.

21:51.940 --> 21:56.720
But if they determine about nothing, which it is wicked to believe, or if we do believe

21:56.720 --> 22:02.560
it, let us neither sacrifice, nor pray, nor swear by them, nor do anything else, which

22:02.560 --> 22:05.180
we do as if the gods were present and lived with us.

22:05.760 --> 22:11.100
But if, however, the gods determine about none of the things which concern us, I am

22:11.100 --> 22:16.300
able to determine about myself, and I can acquire about that which is useful, and that

22:16.300 --> 22:20.480
is useful to every man which is conformable to his own constitution and nature.

22:21.360 --> 22:27.840
But my nature is rational, and social, and my city and country, as far as I am Antoninus,

22:28.040 --> 22:28.600
is Rome.

22:29.320 --> 22:31.740
But so far as I am a man, it is the world.

22:32.400 --> 22:37.000
The things then which are useful to these cities are alone useful to me.

22:39.760 --> 22:43.600
Whatever happens to every man, this is for the interest of the universal.

22:44.220 --> 22:45.320
This might be sufficient.

22:46.020 --> 22:51.140
But further thou wilt observe this also as a general truth, if thou dost observe, that

22:51.140 --> 22:54.900
whatever is profitable to any man is profitable also to other men.

22:55.840 --> 23:01.720
But let the word profitable be taken here in the common sense as said of things of the

23:01.720 --> 23:02.320
more bad.

23:04.940 --> 23:09.700
As it happens to thee in the amphitheater and such places, that the continual sight

23:09.700 --> 23:15.520
of the same things, and the uniformity make the spectacle wearisome, so it is in the whole

23:15.520 --> 23:16.120
of life.

23:16.700 --> 23:20.480
For all things above, below, are the same, and from the same.

23:21.200 --> 23:22.220
How long then?

23:25.860 --> 23:30.720
Think continually that all kinds of men, and all kinds of pursuits, and of all nations

23:30.720 --> 23:36.780
are dead, so that thy thoughts come down even to Philistion, and Phoebus, and Oregonian.

23:37.780 --> 23:40.340
Now turn thy thoughts to the other kinds of men.

23:40.940 --> 23:46.020
To that place, then, we must remove, where there are so many great orators, so many noble

23:46.020 --> 23:52.200
philosophers, Heraclitus, Pythagoras, Socrates, so many heroes of former days, so many

23:52.200 --> 23:55.360
generals after them, and tyrants.

23:55.800 --> 24:02.600
Besides these, Eudoxus, Hipparchus, Archimedes, and other men of acute natural talents, great

24:02.600 --> 24:08.680
minds, lovers of labor, versatile, confident, mockers even of the perishable and ephemeral

24:08.680 --> 24:12.220
life of man, as Menippus and such as are like him.

24:12.900 --> 24:17.060
As to all these, consider that they have long been in the dust.

24:17.880 --> 24:20.020
What harm, then, is this to them?

24:20.020 --> 24:23.300
And what to those whose names are altogether unknown?

24:24.280 --> 24:30.040
One thing here is worth a great deal, to pass thy life in truth and justice, with a benevolent

24:30.040 --> 24:33.080
disposition even to liars and unjust men.

24:35.800 --> 24:41.660
Thou art not dissatisfied, I suppose, because thou weighest only so many leader, and not

24:41.660 --> 24:42.240
three hundred.

24:43.100 --> 24:47.260
Be not dissatisfied, then, that thou must live only so many years, and not more.

24:47.260 --> 24:53.540
For as thou art satisfied with the amount of substance which has been assigned to thee,

24:54.060 --> 24:56.140
so be content with the time.

24:59.820 --> 25:04.600
Let us try to persuade them, but act even against their will when the principles of

25:04.600 --> 25:06.060
justice lead that way.

25:06.560 --> 25:12.060
If, however, any man using force stands in thy way, betake thyself to contentment and

25:12.060 --> 25:16.900
tranquility, and at the same time employ the hindrance toward the exercise of some other

25:16.900 --> 25:22.760
virtue, and remember that thy attempt was with a reservation, that thou didst not desire

25:22.760 --> 25:24.140
to do impossibilities.

25:25.020 --> 25:26.620
What, then, didst thou desire?

25:27.680 --> 25:33.000
Some such effort is this, but thou attainest thy object if the things to which thou wast

25:33.000 --> 25:34.200
move are accomplished.

25:37.160 --> 25:42.940
He who loves fame considers another man's activity to be his own good, and he who loves

25:42.940 --> 25:49.000
pleasure his own sensations, but he who has understanding considers his own acts to be

25:49.000 --> 25:49.920
his own good.

25:52.220 --> 25:56.980
It is in our power to have no opinion about a thing, and not to be disturbed in our soul,

25:57.280 --> 26:00.460
for things themselves have no natural power to form our judgments.

26:03.760 --> 26:08.940
Accustom thyself to attend carefully to what is said by another, and as much as it is possible

26:08.940 --> 26:10.760
be in the speaker's mind.

26:12.740 --> 26:16.700
That which is not good for the swarm, neither is it good for the bee.

26:19.580 --> 26:24.860
If sailors abused the helmsman, or the sick the doctor, would they listen to anybody else?

26:25.280 --> 26:30.620
And how could the helmsman secure the safety of those in the ship, or the doctor, health of

26:30.620 --> 26:31.720
those whom he attends?

26:34.680 --> 26:39.580
How many together with whom I came into the world are already gone out of it?

26:42.040 --> 26:47.820
To the jaundiced honey tastes bitter, and to those bitten by mad dogs water causes fear,

26:48.360 --> 26:50.920
and to little children the ball is a fine thing.

26:51.760 --> 26:52.920
Why then am I angry?

26:53.440 --> 26:58.400
Dost thou think that a false opinion has less power than the bile in the jaundiced, or the

26:58.400 --> 27:00.640
poison in him who is bitten by a mad dog?

27:03.640 --> 27:07.140
No man will hinder thee from living according to the reason of thy nature.

27:07.140 --> 27:11.960
Nothing will happen to the country, to the reason of the universal nature.

27:15.900 --> 27:21.080
What kind of people are those whom men wish to please, and for what objects, and by what

27:21.080 --> 27:22.000
kinds of acts?

27:22.720 --> 27:27.960
How soon time will cover all things, and how many it has covered already.

27:42.080 --> 27:43.480
Thank you.

